@node FSet API Reference
@chapter FSet API Reference

@c &&& I haven't mentioned compatibility methods for lists.  Should they go in here, or somewhere else?

This chapter documents the FSet 2 API.  All symbols should be accessed via package @code{fset2}.

All FSet classes are structure classes.  Each has a predicate, whose name is that of the class
followed by a question mark, e.g., @code{set?}.

Most FSet abstract types have two implementations (with a possibility of more in the future).  There
are generic constructor functions and macros, which do not specify an implementation, and do not
accept custom comparison or hashing functions; they are recommended for situations in which these
details are unimportant.  Implementation-specific constructors are also provided that do accept
these customizations.

In most cases, operations that require a single collection take it as the first argument.  (CL is
itself inconsistent about this; the collection is more commonly the second argument
(e.g. @code{member}, @code{assoc}), but then there's @code{aref}.)  The exceptions are the
higher-order operators @code{image} (or @code{map-image}), @code{filter}, and @code{reduce}, which
all take the function to call first, to be consistent with one another and with CL's @code{mapcar},
@code{remove-if-not}, and @code{reduce} respectively; and most of the shadowed CL sequence
operations --- @code{find} @href{Shadowed CL sequence operations, etc.} (obviously, I couldn't
change the argument orders of these, if the shadowed versions are to be compatible).

This chapter uses the notation [@i{a} .. @i{b}) for an integer interval inclusive of @i{a} and
exclusive of @i{b}.

@deftp {Data type} collection
The root class of the FSet functional collections hierarchy.
@end deftp

@c ================================================================================
@node Notes on Time Complexity
@section Notes on Time Complexity

Most lookup operations, and most ``point update'' operations (which update a single element or
pair), have O(log @i{n}) time complexity.  In these cases, @i{n} refers to the size of the
collection.

FSet has several operations, such as @code{union} on sets, that combine two collections.  These
operations are normally O(@i{n}), but there are two exceptions.  On one hand, if the collections are
not of the same type and organization, more generic methods are invoked that are O(@i{n} log @i{n}).
On the other, under some circumstances they can take O(log @i{n}) time.  The latter occurs if they
are @dfn{historically related}: one is the result of making a small number of point updates on the
6other, or they are both the result of making such updates on a common ancestor.  Under such
circumstances, their internal trees will be largely shared; the implementations detect and exploit
this sharing to elide most of the work.

Also, even when these operations do take O(@i{n}) time, there's the question of exactly what @i{n}
corresponds to.  For many of these operations, in the worst case, it's the sum of the two sizes, but
in typical cases it's often closer to the minimum of the two.  For some operations, notably
intersection (including map and bag intersection and bag product), it's the minimum even in the
worst case.  For asymmetrical operations like set-difference, it's the size of the left operand.

Since seqs are implemented as WB-trees, indexing takes O(log @i{n}) time.  This seems to contrast
poorly with the O(1) time you would get with a Lisp vector.  However, it applies only when you're
doing true random access into the seq, which is a relatively rare case in practice.  More common is
to iterate over the seq or a subrange of it; using @href{Macro do-seq, @code{do-seq}} or the
@href{Stateful Iterators, stateful} or @href{Functional Iterators, functional iterators}, there is a
logarithmic setup time, but after that the iteration takes amortized constant time per element.

@c ================================================================================
@node Sets
@section Sets

A set is an unordered collection of values without duplicates, called its elements or members, with
efficient operations to add or remove a value and to test whether the set contains a value.  Adding
a value to a set that already contains it, or removing one from a set that does not contain it,
results in the same set.

Although sets are conceptually unordered, FSet imposes an order for its own purposes.  The WB
implementation allows you to @href{Custom Comparison and Hash Functions, control} this ordering.

The default implementation of sets is currently CHAMP (@code{ch-set}).  The WB implementation
(@code{wb-set}) is also available.

@deftp {Data type} set
The abstract class for FSet functional sets.
@end deftp

@defun empty-set
Constructor function.  Returns an empty set of the default implementation.
@end defun

@defmac set @r{&rest} subforms
Constructor macro.  Constructs a set of the default implementation according to the supplied
argument subforms.  Each argument subform can be an expression, whose value will be an element of
the result set; or a list of the form @code{($ @var{expression})}, in which case the expression must
evaluate to a set, all of whose elements become elements of the result set.
@end defmac

@deftp {Data type} ch-set
Functional sets implemented using CHAMP trees.  These print as:

@example
##@{ @i{e0} @i{e1} ... @}[@i{compare-fn}]
@end example

The comparison function is printed only if it is not @code{compare}.
@end deftp

@deftp {Data type} wb-set
Functional sets implemented using WB-trees.  These print as:

@example
#@{ @i{e0} @i{e1} ... @}[@i{compare-fn}]
@end example

The comparison function is printed only if it is not @code{compare}.
@end deftp

@defun empty-ch-set @r{&key} compare-fn-name
@defunx empty-wb-set @r{&key} compare-fn-name
Constructor function.  Returns an empty wb-set.  By default, it will be ordered by @code{compare}.
To use a custom ordering, supply the comparison function name (a symbol) as @code{compare-fn-name};
for @code{ch-set}, a hash function must have been defined for it using @href{define-hash-function,
@code{define-hash-function}}.
@end defun

@defmac ch-set @r{&rest} subforms
@defmacx wb-set @r{&rest} subforms
Constructor macro.  Constructs a @code{ch-set} or @code{wb-set} according to the supplied argument
subforms.  Each argument subform can be an expression, whose value will be an element of the result
set; or a list of the form @code{($ @var{expression})}, in which case the expression must evaluate
to a set, all of whose elements become elements of the result set.
@end defmac

@defmac ch-custom-set compare-fn-name @r{&rest} subforms
@defmacx wb-custom-set compare-fn-name @r{&rest} subforms
Constructor macro.  Constructs a @code{ch-set} or @code{wb-set} with a custom organization,
according to the supplied argument subforms.  @code{compare-fn-name} must be a symbol naming the
desired comparison function; for @code{ch-custom-set}, a hash function must have been defined for it
using @href{define-hash-function, @code{define-hash-function}}.  Each of @code{args} can be an
expression, whose value will be an element of the result set; or a list of the form @code{($
@var{expression})}, in which case the expression must evaluate to a set, all of whose elements become
elements of the result set.
@end defmac

@c --------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Set Operations
@subsection Set Operations

@deffn Method  {empty? (set)} @ s
Returns true iff the set is empty.  O(1).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {size (set)} @ s
@deffnx Method {set-size (set)} @ s
Returns the number of elements in the set.  O(1).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {arb (set)} @ s
Returns an arbitrary element of the set.  Specifically, on a nonempty set, returns two values: an
arbitrary element and true; on an empty set, returns two false values.  Please note that
``arbitrary'' does not mean ``randomly selected''; it simply means that the sole postcondition is
that the returned value is an element of the set --- FSet can pick any convenient element.  O(1).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {contains? (set t)} @ s x
Returns true iff @var{x} is an element of @var{s}.  O(log @i{n}).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {lookup (set t)} @ s x
If @var{s} contains an element equal to @var{x}, according to its comparison function, returns two
values, true and the element found; else false and @code{nil}.  (This is useful for canonicalizing
instances.)  O(log @i{n}).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {with (set t)} @ s x
Returns a set, of the same class and organization as @var{s}, that contains all elements of @var{s}
and also @var{x}.  If @var{s} already contained a value equal to @var{x}, according to its
comparison function, returns @var{s} itself.  (This is so you can find out whether the element was
added simply by calling @code{eq} on @var{s} and the result.)

@defmac includef place x
A @href{Quasi-Mutating Operators, modify macro} that expands to @code{with}.  If @var{place} holds a
set, updates it so the set now contains @var{x}.
@end defmac
@end deffn

@deffn Method {less (set t)} @ s x
Returns a set, of the same class and organization as @var{s}, that contains all elements of @var{s}
except @var{x}.  If @var{s} did not contain a value equal to @var{x}, according to its comparison
function, returns @var{s} itself.  (This is so you can find out whether the element was removed
simply by calling @code{eq} on @var{s} and the result.)

@defmac excludef place x
A @href{Quasi-Mutating Operators, modify macro} that expands to @code{less}.  If @var{place} holds a
set, updates it so the set does not contain @var{x}.
@end defmac
@end deffn

@deffn Method {index (set t)} @ s x
If @var{s} contains @var{x}, returns the index of @var{x} within the ordering of @var{s}; otherwise
@code{nil}.  O(log @i{n}).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {at-index (set fixnum)} @ s idx
Returns the element at index @var{idx} within the ordering of @var{s}.  (On a @code{wb-set}, this is
the same as @code{at-rank}.)  @var{rank} must be in [0 .. size(s)); otherwise, signals an error of
type @code{simple-type-error}.  O(log @i{n}).
@end deffn

@anchor{union}
@deffn Method {union (set set)} @ s1 s2 @r{&key}
Returns a set of the same type and organization as @var{s1}, that contains all elements that are in
either @var{s1} or @var{s2}.  Implements @href{Left Preference, left preference}: for any pair of
equal objects in the two sets, the result contains the instance that was in @var{s1}.  @href{Notes
on Time Complexity, Normally O(@i{n})}.
@end deffn

@anchor{intersection}
@deffn Method {intersection (set set)} @ s1 s2 @r{&key}
Returns a set of the same type and organization as @var{s1}, that contains all elements that are in
both @var{s1} and @var{s2}.  Implements @href{Left Preference, left preference}: for any pair of
equal objects in the two sets, the result contains the instance that was in @var{s1}.  @href{Notes
on Time Complexity, Normally O(@i{n})}.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {set-difference (set set)} @ s1 s2
Returns a set of the same type and organization as @var{s1}, that contains all elements that are in
@var{s1} and not in @var{s2}.  @href{Notes on Time Complexity, Normally O(@i{n})}.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {set-difference-2 (set set)} @ s1 s2
Returns, as two values: () a set of the same type and organization as @var{s1}, that contains all
elements that are in @var{s1} and not in @var{s2}, and () a set of the same type and organization as
@var{s2}, that contains all elements that are in @var{s2} and not in @var{s1}.  @href{Notes on Time
Complexity, Normally O(@i{n})}.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {subset? (set set)} @ s1 s2
Returns true iff every element of @var{s1} is also in @var{s2}.  @href{Notes on Time Complexity,
Normally O(@i{n})}.
@end deffn

@defun proper-subset? set1 set2
Returns true iff every element of @var{s1} is also in @var{s2}, and @var{s1} is smaller than
@var{s2}.  @href{Notes on Time Complexity, Normally O(@i{n})}.
@end defun

@deffn Method {disjoint? (set set)} @ s1 s2
Returns true iff @var{s1} and @var{s2} have no elements in common.  @href{Notes on Time Complexity,
Normally O(@i{n})}.
@end deffn

@anchor{Macro do-set}
@defmac do-set @r{(@var{var} @var{set} &optional @var{value}) &body} body
For each element of @var{set}, binds @var{var} to it and executes @var{body}.  When done,
returns @var{value} if supplied, otherwise @code{nil}.
@end defmac

@anchor{iterator (set)}
@deffn Method {iterator (set)} @ s @r{&key}
Returns a @href{Stateful Iterators, stateful iterator} over the set.
@end deffn

@anchor{fun-iterator (set)}
@deffn Method {fun-iterator (set)} @ s @r{&key}
Returns a @href{Functional Iterators, functional iterator} over the set.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {filter (function set)} @ pred s
@deffnx Method {filter (symbol set)} @ pred s
@deffnx Method {filter (map set)} @ pred s
@c Document (set set) and (bag set) too?
Returns a new set, of the same type and organization as @var{s}, containing only those elements that
satisfy @var{pred}.  @var{pred} must be a function, an fbound symbol, or a boolean-valued map.
O(@i{n} ⋅ tc(@var{pred})) + O(@i{r} log @i{r}), where tc(@var{pred}) is the time complexity of
@var{pred} and @i{r} is the size of the result.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {partition (function set)} @ pred s
@deffnx Method {partition (symbol set)} @ pred s
@deffnx Method {partition (map set)} @ pred s
Equivalent to @code{(values (filter pred s) (filter (complement pred) s))} when @var{pred} is a
function.  Returns two values: first, a new set, of the same type and organization as @var{s},
containing only those elements that satisfy @var{pred}; second, a similar set containing only those
elements that do @emph{not} satisfy @var{pred}.  @var{pred} must be a function, an fbound symbol, or
a boolean-valued map.  O(@i{n} ⋅ tc(@var{pred})) + O(@i{r} log @i{r}), where tc(@var{pred}) is the
time complexity of @var{pred} and @i{r} is the size of the result.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {image (function set)} @ fn s @r{&key} compare-fn-name
@deffnx Method {image (symbol set)} @ fn s @r{&key} compare-fn-name
@deffnx Method {image (map set)} @ fn s @r{&key} compare-fn-name
Returns a set containing the values of @var{fn} applied to all the elements of @var{s}.  Since the
result is a set, its elements will not necessarily correspond one-to-one to those of @var{s}; it
will impose its own ordering, and will be smaller than @var{s} if @var{fn} returns the same value on
two or more elements of @var{s}.  The result will be of the same type as @var{s}.
@var{compare-fn-name}, if supplied, will control its organization; otherwise, that will also be the
same as for @var{s}.  @var{fn} must be a function, an fbound symbol, or a map.  O(@i{n} ⋅
tc(@var{fn})) + O(@i{r} log @i{r}), where tc(@var{fn}) is the time complexity of @var{fn} and @i{r}
is the size of the result.

@defmac imagef place fn
A @href{Quasi-Mutating Operators, modify macro} that expands to @code{image}.  If @var{place} holds a
set, updates it so the place now contains the image of the set under @var{fn}.
@end defmac
@end deffn

@deffn Method {reduce (function set)} @ fn s @r{&key} key @r{(@var{initial-value} nil)}
@deffnx Method {reduce (function set)} @ fn s @r{&key} key @r{(@var{initial-value} nil)}
Calls @var{fn} repeatedly with two arguments, a state variable and the next element of @var{s},
storing the result of each call back into the state variable, and finally returning that value.  If
@var{initial-value} is supplied, it is used as the initial value of the state variable.  Otherwise:
if @var{s} is of size 2 or larger, the initial value is computed by calling @var{fn} on the first
two elements, then proceeding with the third; if @var{s} is a singleton, the result is its sole
element; if @var{s} is empty, the result is obtained by calling @var{fn} with no arguments.  (Time
complexity depends on the behavior of @var{fn}.)
@end deffn

@deffn Method {find (t set)} @ item s @r{&key} key test
Scans linearly through @var{s} to find an element that matches @var{item} according to @var{key} and
@var{test}.  For each element of @var{s}, @var{key}, a function that defaults to the identity
function, is called on it, and then @var{test} is called on @var{item} and the result; if it returns
true, @code{find} returns the element.  If no match is found, @code{find} returns @code{nil}.
@var{test} defaults to @code{equal?}, not @code{eql}.

Normally O(@i{n}), but as a special case, if @var{test} is @code{equal?}, @var{key} is not supplied,
and the set's comparison function is @code{compare}, this does an O(log @i{n}) lookup.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {find-if (t set)} @ pred s @r{&key} key
Scans linearly through @var{s} to find an element for which the result of calling @var{key} on it
satisfies @var{pred}.  @var{key} and @var{pred} must be functions or fbound symbols.  @var{key}
defaults to the identity function.  Returns the element found, or @code{nil} if none.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {find-if-not (t set)} @ pred s @r{&key} key
Scans linearly through @var{s} to find an element for which the result of calling @var{key} on it
does not satisfy @var{pred}.  @var{key} and @var{pred} must be functions or fbound symbols.
@var{key} defaults to the identity function.  Returns the element found, or @code{nil} if none.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {count (t set)} @ item s @r{&key} key test
Scans linearly through @var{s}, counting the number of elements that match @var{item} according to
@var{key} and @var{test}.  For each element of @var{s}, @var{key} is called on it, and then
@var{test} is called on @var{item} and the result; if it returns true, the element is counted.
Returns the count.  @var{key} and @var{test} must be functions or fbound symbols.  @var{key} defaults
to the identity function; @var{test} defaults to @code{equal?}, not @code{eql}.

Normally O(@i{n}), but as a special case, if @var{test} is @code{equal?}, @var{key} is not supplied,
and the set's comparison function is @code{compare}, this does an O(log @i{n}) lookup to return 1 or
0.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {count-if (t set)} @ pred s @r{&key} key
Scans linearly through @var{s} to count the elements for which the result of calling @var{key} on
them satisfies @var{pred}.  Returns the count.  @var{pred} and @var{key} must be functions or fbound
symbols.  @var{key} defaults to the identity function.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {count-if-not (t set)} @ pred s @r{&key} key
Scans linearly through @var{s} to count the elements for which the result of calling @var{key} on
them does not satisfy @var{pred}.  Returns the count.  @var{pred} and @var{key} must be functions or
fbound symbols.  @var{key} defaults to the identity function.
@end deffn


@c --------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node WB-Set Operations
@subsection WB-Set Operations

These operations make use of the ordering of the set, as determined by its comparison function.
They are not defined on CHAMP sets.

@deffn Method {rank (wb-set t)} @ s x
[@code{wb-set} only.]  If @var{s} contains @var{x}, returns the rank of @var{x} in the ordering
defined by the comparison function of @var{s}, and a true second value. If @var{x} is not in the set,
the second value is false, and the first value is the rank that @var{x} would have if it were added.
Note that if there are values that are unequal but equivalent to @var{x}, an arbitrary order will be
imposed on them for this purpose; but another collection that is @code{equal?} but not @code{eq} to
this one will in general order them differently.  O(log @i{n}).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {at-rank (wb-set fixnum)} @ s rank
[@code{wb-set} only.]  Returns the element whose rank is @var{rank}.  @var{rank} must be in [0
.. size(@var{m})).  Note that if there are values that are unequal but equivalent in @var{s}, an
arbitrary order will be imposed on them for this purpose; but another collection that is
@code{equal?} but not @code{eq} to this one will in general order them differently.  O(log @i{n}).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {least (wb-set)} @ s
[@code{wb-set} only.]  If @var{s} is nonempty, returns the element at rank 0 and a true second
value; otherwise, @code{nil} and false.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {greatest (wb-set)} @ s
[@code{wb-set} only.]  If @var{s} is nonempty, returns the element with the largest rank and a true
second value; otherwise, @code{nil} and false.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {split-from (wb-set t)} @ s x
[@code{wb-set} only.]  Returns the subset of @var{s} with elements greater than or equal to @var{x}.
O(log @i{n}).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {split-above (wb-set t)} @ s x
[@code{wb-set} only.]  Returns the subset of @var{s} with elements strictly greater than @var{x}.
O(log @i{n}) in general; O(1) if @var{x} is the result of @code{(arb @var{s})}.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {split-through (wb-set t)} @ s x
[@code{wb-set} only.]  Returns the subset of @var{s} with elements less than or equal to @var{x}.
O(log @i{n}).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {split-below (wb-set t)} @ s x
[@code{wb-set} only.]  Returns the subset of @var{s} with elements strictly less than @var{x}.
O(log @i{n}) in general; O(1) if @var{x} is the result of @code{(arb @var{s})}.
@end deffn


@c ================================================================================
@node Maps
@section Maps

A map is an unordered collection of keys without duplicates, each key having an associated value;
with efficient operations to add a key/value pair, remove a key with its value, and to retrieve the
value for a key.  Adding a key/value pair to a map that already contains it, or removing a key from
a map that does not contain it, result in the same map.

Although maps are conceptually unordered, FSet imposes an order for its own purposes.  The WB
implementation allows you to @href{Custom Comparison and Hash Functions, control} this ordering.

The default implementation of maps is currently CHAMP (@code{ch-map}).  The WB implementation
(@code{wb-map}) is also available.

@deftp {Data type} map
The abstract class for FSet functional maps.
@end deftp

@defun empty-map @r{&key} @r{(@var{default} nil)} no-default?
Constructor function.  Returns an empty map of the default implementation.  If @var{default} is
supplied, that will be the map's @href{Map and Seq Defaults, default}; if @var{no-default?} is true,
the map will have no default.
@end defun

@defmac map @r{&rest} subforms
Constructor macro.  Constructs a map of the default implementation according to the supplied
argument subforms.  Each argument subform can be a list of the form @code{(@var{key-expr}
@var{value-expr})}, denoting a mapping from the value of @var{key-expr} to the value of
@var{value-expr}; or a list of the form @code{($ @var{expression})}, in which case the expression
must evaluate to a map, denoting all its mappings; or the symbol @code{:default}, followed by a
form; or the symbol @code{:no-default}.  If @code{:default} is supplied, the map's @href{Map and Seq
Defaults, default} is the value of the subsequent form; if @code{:no-default} is supplied, the map
has no default; if neither, the map's default is @code{nil}.

As a convenience, if a subform is @code{($ @var{expression})} and the expression evaluates to
@code{nil}, it will be treated as an empty map.  The result is constructed from the denoted mappings
in left-to-right order; so if a given key is supplied by more than one argument subform, its
associated value will be given by the rightmost such subform.
@end defmac

@deftp {Data type} ch-map
Functional maps implemented using CHAMP trees.  These print as:

@example
##@{| (@i{k0 v0}) (@i{k1 v1}) ... @}[@i{key-compare-fn};@i{val-compare-fn}]
@end example

The comparison functions are printed only if they are not @code{compare}.
@end deftp

@deftp {Data type} wb-map
Functional maps implemented using WB-trees.  These print as:

@example
#@{| (@i{k0 v0}) (@i{k1 v1}) ... @}[@i{key-compare-fn};@i{val-compare-fn}]
@end example

The comparison functions are printed only if they are not @code{compare}.
@end deftp

@defmac ch-map @r{&rest} subforms
@defmacx wb-map @r{&rest} subforms
Constructor macro.  Constructs a @code{ch-map} or @code{wb-map} according to the supplied argument
subforms.  Each argument subform can be a list of the form @code{(@var{key-expr} @var{value-expr})},
denoting a mapping from the value of @var{key-expr} to the value of @var{value-expr}; or a list of
the form @code{($ @var{expression})}, in which case the expression must evaluate to a map, denoting
all its mappings; or the symbol @code{:default}, followed by a form; or the symbol
@code{:no-default}.  If @code{:default} is supplied, the map's @href{Map and Seq Defaults, default}
is the value of the subsequent form; if @code{:no-default} is supplied, the map has no default; if
neither, the map's default is @code{nil}.

As a convenience, if a subform is @code{($ @var{expression})} and the expression evaluates to
@code{nil}, it will be treated as an empty map.  The result is constructed from the denoted mappings
in left-to-right order; so if a given key is supplied by more than one argument subform, its
associated value will be given by the rightmost such subform.
@end defmac

@defmac ch-custom-map key-compare-fn-name val-compare-fn-name @r{&rest} subforms
@defmacx wb-custom-map key-compare-fn-name val-compare-fn-name @r{&rest} subforms
Constructor macro.  Constructs a @code{ch-map} or @code{wb-map} with a custom organization according
to the supplied argument subforms.  @var{key-compare-fn-name} and @var{val-compare-fn-name} must be
symbols naming the comparison functions to be used for keys and values respectively (you can use
@code{nil} as a synonym of @code{compare}).  For @code{ch-custom-map}, a hash function must have
been defined for it using @href{define-hash-function, @code{define-hash-function}}.  (The value
comparison is used for detecting redundant @code{with} operations, and a few other things, such as
@code{range} and @code{map-difference-2}.)

Each argument subform can be a list of the form @code{(@var{key-expr} @var{value-expr})}, denoting a
mapping from the value of @var{key-expr} to the value of @var{value-expr}; or a list of the form
@code{($ @var{expression})}, in which case the expression must evaluate to a map, denoting all its
mappings; or the symbol @code{:default}, followed by a form; or the symbol @code{:no-default}.  If
@code{:default} is supplied, the map's @href{Map and Seq Defaults, default} is the value of the
subsequent form; if @code{:no-default} is supplied, the map has no default; if neither, the map's
default is @code{nil}.

As a convenience, if a subform is @code{($ @var{expression})} and the expression evaluates to
@code{nil}, it will be treated as an empty map.  The result is constructed from the denoted mappings
in left-to-right order; so if a given key is supplied by more than one argument subform, its
associated value will be given by the rightmost such subform.
@end defmac

@c --------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Map Operations
@subsection Map Operations

@deffn Method  {empty? (map)} @ m
Returns true iff the map is empty.  O(1).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {size (map)} @ m
Returns the number of key-value pairs in the map.  O(1).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {arb (map)} @ m
Returns an arbitrary pair of the map.  Specifically, on a nonempty map, returns three values: an
arbitrary key, its associated value, and true; on an empty map, returns three false values.  Please
note that ``arbitrary'' does not mean ``randomly selected''; it simply means that the sole
postcondition is that the map contains the pair returned --- FSet can pick any convenient pair.
O(1).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {contains? (map t)} @ m k @r{&optional} v
If @var{v} is not supplied, returns true iff the domain of @var{m} contains @var{k}.  If @var{v} is
supplied, returns true iff @var{m} maps @var{k} to @var{v}.  O(log @i{n}).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {domain-contains? (map t)} @ m k
Returns true iff the domain of @var{m} contains @var{k}.  (This is now redundant with two-argument
@code{contains?}, and is mildly deprecated.  For most of FSet's history, @code{contains?} on a map
required three arguments; so it was all but useless, and you had to use @code{domain-contains?}
instead.  Fortunately, I finally came to my senses and fixed @code{contains?} to accept two
arguments.)  O(log @i{n}).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {range-contains? (map t)} @ m v
Returns true iff the range of @var{m} contains @var{v}, that is, if any key is mapped to @var{v}.
O(@i{n}).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {lookup (map t)} @ m k
If @var{m} contains a key equal to @var{k}, according to its key comparison function, returns three
values: the corresponding value, true, and the key found; otherwise, the map's @href{Map and Seq
Defaults, default}, false, and @code{nil}.  If the key is not found and the map has no default,
signals an error of type @code{map-domain-error}.  O(log @i{n}).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {with (map t)} @ m k v
Returns a map, of the same class and organization as @var{m}, that contains all pairs of @var{m}
whose key is not equal to @var{k} (according to its key comparison function), and also maps @var{k}
to @var{v}.  If @var{m} already contained a key equal to @var{k}, and the corresponding value is
equal to @var{v} according to its value comparison function, returns @var{m} itself.  (This is so
you can find out whether the pair was added or updated simply by calling @code{eq} on @var{m} and
the result.)

@defmac includef place k v
A @href{Quasi-Mutating Operators, modify macro} that expands to @code{with}.  If @var{place} holds a
map, updates it so the map now maps @var{k} to @var{v}.
@end defmac
@end deffn

@deffn Method {less (map t)} @ m k
Returns a map, of the same class and organization as @var{m}, that contains all pairs of @var{m}
whose key is not equal to @var{k}.  If @var{m} did not contain a key equal to @var{k}, according to
its comparison function, returns @var{m} itself.  (This is so you can find out whether the pair was
removed simply by calling @code{eq} on @var{} and the result.)

@defmac excludef place k
A @href{Quasi-Mutating Operators, modify macro} that expands to @code{less}.  If @var{place} holds a
map, updates it so the set does not contain a key @var{k}.
@end defmac
@end deffn

@deffn Method {index (map t)} @ m k
If @var{m} contains key @var{k}, returns the index of @var{k} within the ordering of @var{m}; otherwise
@code{nil}.  O(log @i{n}).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {at-index (map fixnum)} @ m idx
Returns the pair at index @var{idx} within the ordering of @var{m}.  (On a @code{wb-m}, this is
the same as @code{at-rank}.)  @var{rank} must be in [0 .. size(s)); otherwise, signals an error of
type @code{simple-type-error}.  O(log @i{n}).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {domain (map)} @ m
Returns the domain (set of keys) of @var{m}, as a set of the same implementation (WB or CHAMP), and
using @var{m}'s key ordering as its ordering.  O(@i{n}), but with a relatively small constant
factor.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {range (map)} @ m
Returns the range of @var{m} (the set of values to which any key is mapped), as a set of the same
implementation (WB or CHAMP), and using @var{m}'s value ordering as its ordering.  O(@i{n} log
@i{n}).
@end deffn

@anchor{map-union}
@deffn Method {map-union (map map)} @ m1 m2 @r{&optional} val-fn
Returns a map containing all the keys of @var{m1} and @var{m2}, where the value for each key
contained in only one map is the value from that map, and the value for each key contained in both
maps is the result of calling @var{val-fn} on the value from @var{m1} and the value from @var{m2}.
@var{val-fn} defaults to simply returning its second argument, so the entries in @var{m2} simply
shadow those in @var{m1}.  The @href{Map and Seq Defaults, default} for the new map is: if both maps
have defaults, the result of calling @var{val-fn} on those defaults; if only one map has a default,
that default; otherwise none.

@code{map-union} assumes that @var{val-fn} is idempotent, i.e., if the two values passed to
@var{val-fn} are equal, @var{val-fn} must return the same value; it often elides calls to @var{val-fn}
on that basis.

If @var{val-fn} returns the symbol @code{:no-value} as a second value, the result will contain no
pair with the corresponding key.

Implements @href{Left Preference, left preference}: for any pair of equal keys in the two maps, the
result contains the instance that was in @var{m1}; the associated value, if the two values are
equal, is also that in @var{m1}.

@href{Notes on Time Complexity, Normally O(@i{n})}.
@end deffn

@anchor{map-intersection}
@deffn Method {map-intersection (map map)} @ m1 m2 @r{&optional} val-fn
Returns a map containing all the keys that are in the domains of both @var{m1} and @var{m2}, where
the value for each key is the result of calling @var{val-fn} on the value from @var{m1} and the
value from @var{m2}.  @var{val-fn} defaults to simply returning its second argument, so the entries
in @var{m2} simply shadow those in @var{m1}.  The @href{Map and Seq Defaults, default} for the new
map is the result of calling @var{val-fn} on the defaults for the two maps, if they both have
defaults; else none.

@code{map-intersection} assumes that @var{val-fn} is idempotent, i.e., if the two values passed to
@var{val-fn} are equal, @var{val-fn} must return the same value; it often elides calls to @var{val-fn}
on that basis.

If @var{val-fn} returns @code{:no-value} as a second value, the result will contain no pair with the
corresponding key.

Implements @href{Left Preference, left preference}: for any pair of equal keys in the two maps, the
result contains the instance that was in @var{m1}; the associated value, if the two values are
equal, is also that in @var{m1}.

@href{Notes on Time Complexity, Normally O(@i{n})}.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {map-difference-2 (map map)} @ m1 m2
Returns, as two values: a map containing all the pairs that are in @var{m1} but not @var{m2}, and
one containing all the pairs that are in @var{m2} but not @var{m1}.

The default for each returned map is that of its corresponding argument, if it has a default, except
if the defaults are equal, in which case neither returned map has a default.

@href{Notes on Time Complexity, Normally O(@i{n})}.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {restrict (map set)} @ m s
Returns a map containing only those pairs of @var{m} whose keys are also in @var{s}.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {restrict-not (map set)} @ m s
Returns a map containing only those pairs of @var{m} whose keys are @emph{not} also in @var{s}.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {filter (function map)} @ pred m
@deffnx Method {filter (symbol map)} @ pred m
Returns a new map, of the same type and organization as @var{m}, containing only those pairs that
satisfy @var{pred}.  @var{pred} may be specified as a function or an fbound symbol.  O(@i{n}
⋅ tc(@var{pred})) + O(@i{r} log @i{r}), where tc(@var{pred}) is the time complexity of @var{pred}
and @i{r} is the size of the result.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {map-image (function map)} @ f m @r{&key} key-compare-fn-name val-compare-fn-name default no-default?
@deffnx Method {map-image (symbol map)} @ f m @r{&key} key-compare-fn-name val-compare-fn-name default no-default?
Returns a map containing the result of applying @var{fn} to each pair of @var{m}.  That is, @var{fn}
is called with both the domain and range values as arguments; it is expected to return two values,
which become the new domain and range values.  @var{fn} may be specified as a function or an fbound
symbol.  @var{key-compare-fn-name} and @var{val-compare-fn-name}, if supplied, control the
organization of the result; the default for each is the corresponding property of @var{m}.  The
default of the returned map is @code{nil} unless a different default is specified by @var{default},
or @var{no-default?} is true.

See also @code{compose}, below.

@defmac map-imagef place fn
A @href{Quasi-Mutating Operators, modify macro} that expands to @code{map-image}.  If @var{place}
holds a map, updates it so the place now contains the image of the map under @var{fn}.
@end defmac
@end deffn

@deffn Method {compose (map map)} @ m1 m2
@deffnx Method {compose (map function)} @ m1 f2
@deffnx Method {compose (map symbol)} @ m1 f2
@deffnx Method {compose (map seq)} @ m1 s2
Composes a map with another map, a function (possibly specified as an fbound symbol), or a seq
(considered as a map from indices to elements).  That is, for each pair in @var{m1}, the result maps
its key to the result of invoking @var{m2}, @var{f2}, or @var{s2} to its value.  If @var{m1} has a
default, the value of invoking the second argument on that default becomes the default of the
returned map.

In the (map map) and (map seq) cases, takes O(@i{m} log @i{n}) time, where @i{m} is the size of
@var{m1} and @i{n} is the size of @var{m2} or @var{s2}.  In the function cases, it obviously depends
on the behavior of the function; it will be called @i{m} times.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {find (t map)} @ item m @r{&key} key test
Scans linearly through the keys of @var{m} to find an element that matches @var{item} according to
@var{key} and @var{test}.  For each element of @var{s}, @var{key}, a function that defaults to the
identity function, is called on it, and then @var{test} is called on @var{item} and the result; if
it returns true, @code{find} returns two values, the element and its associated value.  If no match
is found, @code{find} returns two @code{nil} values.  @var{test} defaults to @code{equal?}, not
@code{eql}.

Normally O(@i{n}), but as a special case, if @var{test} is @code{equal?}, @var{key} is not supplied,
and the map's key comparison function is @code{compare}, this does an O(log @i{n}) lookup.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {find-if (t map)} @ pred m @r{&key} key
Scans linearly through the keys of @var{m} to find one for which the result of calling @var{key} on it
satisfies @var{pred}.  @var{key} and @var{pred} must be functions or fbound symbols.  @var{key}
defaults to the identity function.  Returns two values, the key found and its associated value, or
two @code{nil} values if none.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {find-if-not (t map)} @ pred m @r{&key} key
Scans linearly through the keys of @var{m} to find one for which the result of calling @var{key} on
it does not satisfy @var{pred}.  @var{key} and @var{pred} must be functions or fbound symbols.
@var{key} defaults to the identity function.  Returns two values, the key found and its associated
value, or two @code{nil} values if none.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {count (t map)} @ item m @r{&key} key test
Scans linearly through the keys of @var{m}, counting the number that match @var{item} according to
@var{key} and @var{test}.  For each key of @var{m}, @var{key} is called on it, and then @var{test}
is called on @var{item} and the result; if it returns true, the key is counted.  Returns the count.
@var{key} and @var{test} must be functions or fbound symbols.  @var{key} defaults to the identity
function; @var{test} defaults to @code{equal?}, not @code{eql}.

Normally O(@i{n}), but as a special case, if @var{test} is @code{equal?}, @var{key} is not supplied,
and the map's key comparison function is @code{compare}, this does an O(log @i{n}) lookup to return
1 or 0.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {count-if (t map)} @ pred m @r{&key} key
Scans linearly through the keys of @var{m} to count those for which the result of calling @var{key} on
them satisfies @var{pred}.  Returns the count.  @var{pred} and @var{key} must be functions or fbound
symbols.  @var{key} defaults to the identity function.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {count-if-not (t map)} @ pred m @r{&key} key
Scans linearly through the keys of @var{m} to count those for which the result of calling @var{key} on
them does not satisfy @var{pred}.  Returns the count.  @var{pred} and @var{key} must be functions or
fbound symbols.  @var{key} defaults to the identity function.
@end deffn

@c --------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node WB-Map Operations
@subsection WB-Map Operations

These operations make use of the ordering of the map, as determined by its key comparison function.
They are not defined on CHAMP maps.

@deffn Method {rank (wb-map t)} @ m x
[@code{wb-map} only.]  If @var{m} contains key @var{x}, returns the rank of @var{x} in the ordering
defined by the key comparison function of @var{m}, and a true second value. If @var{x} is not in the
map, the second value is false, and the first value is the rank that @var{x} would have if it were
added.  Note that if there are keys that are unequal but equivalent to @var{x}, an arbitrary order
will be imposed on them for this purpose; but another collection that is @code{equal?} but not
@code{eq} to this one will in general order them differently.  O(log @i{n}).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {at-rank (wb-map fixnum)} @ m rank
[@code{wb-map} only.]  Returns the pair whose rank is @var{rank}.  @var{rank} must be in [0
.. size(@var{m})).  Note that if there are keys that are unequal but equivalent in @var{m}, an
arbitrary order will be imposed on them for this purpose; but another collection that is
@code{equal?} but not @code{eq} to this one will in general order them differently.  O(log @i{n}).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {least (wb-map)} @ m
[@code{wb-map} only.]  If @var{m} is nonempty, returns the pair at rank 0 and a true third value;
otherwise, @code{nil}, @code{nil}, and false.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {greatest (wb-map)} @ m
[@code{wb-map} only.]  If @var{m} is nonempty, returns the pair with the largest rank and a true
third value; otherwise, @code{nil}, @code{nil}, and false.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {split-from (wb-map t)} @ m x
[@code{wb-map} only.]  Returns the submap of @var{m} with keys greater than or equal to @var{x}.
O(log @i{n}).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {split-above (wb-map t)} @ m x
[@code{wb-map} only.]  Returns the submap of @var{m} with keys strictly greater than @var{x}.
O(log @i{n}) in general; O(1) if @var{x} is the first value of @code{(arb @var{m})}.
@end deffn

@deffn Method {split-through (wb-map t)} @ m x
[@code{wb-map} only.]  Returns the submap of @var{m} with keys less than or equal to @var{x}.
O(log @i{n}).
@end deffn

@deffn Method {split-below (wb-map t)} @ m x
[@code{wb-map} only.]  Returns the submap of @var{m} with keys strictly less than @var{x}.
O(log @i{n}) in general; O(1) if @var{x} is the result of @code{(arb @var{m})}.
@end deffn


@c ================================================================================
@node Bags
@section Bags

@cindex Multiplicity
A bag, also called a multiset, is an unordered collection of values that permits duplicates.  Each
element of the bag has an associated @dfn{multiplicity} (sometimes called ``count''), which is a
positive integer specifying the number of instances of the element in the bag.  As with a set, there
are efficient operations to add a specified number of instances of value, to remove a specified
number of instances, to test whether the bag contains a value, and to retrieve the multiplicity of a
value.  Adding a value to a bag that already contains it adds the specified number of instances to
its multiplicity; removing subtracts the number of instances removed, but once all instances are
removed, further removals have no effect (multiplicities are never negative).

Although bags are conceptually unordered, FSet imposes an order for its own purposes.  The WB
implementation allows you to @href{Custom Comparison and Hash Functions, control} this ordering.

@anchor{bag-union}
@anchor{bag-intersection}
@anchor{bag-sum}
@anchor{bag-product}


